# Persistence Detection

## Objective
If an attacker runs malware once, it disappears after a restart — so attackers configure Windows to automatically relaunch their program every time the computer boots or a user logs in. This is called **Persistence**.

**Real-world example:** an attacker installs `malware.exe`, then configures Windows so that "every time the user logs in, automatically run malware.exe." Even if the victim restarts the PC, the malware returns.

## Commands Run

**Step 1 — Add a Registry Run key** (simulating persistence, using Notepad as a safe stand-in for malware):
```
reg add "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run" /v TestPersistence /t REG_SZ /d "notepad.exe" /f
```

Breakdown:
- `reg add` — adds a registry entry
- `HKCU` — HKEY_CURRENT_USER (affects only the current user)
- `Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run` — a Windows auto-start location; everything here launches at logon
- `/v TestPersistence` — creates a value named `TestPersistence`
- `/t REG_SZ` — value type is plain text
- `/d "notepad.exe"` — program to auto-launch (Notepad used for safety)
- `/f` — forces the change without confirmation

**Step 2 — Verify:**
```
reg query "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run"
```
Expected output: `TestPersistence    REG_SZ    notepad.exe`

**Step 3 — Clean up:**
```
reg delete "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run" /v TestPersistence /f
```

